{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"The advances that have taken place in astronomy,"},{"time":4000,"text":"cosmology and biology, in the last 10 years,"},{"time":11000,"text":"are really extraordinary --"},{"time":15000,"text":"to the point where we know more about our universe and how it works"},{"time":19000,"text":"than many of you might imagine."},{"time":25000,"text":"But there was something else that I've noticed"},{"time":28000,"text":"as those changes were taking place, as people were starting to find out that"},{"time":31000,"text":"hmm ... yeah, there really is a black hole at the center of every galaxy."},{"time":36000,"text":"The science writers and editors -- I shouldn't say science writers,"},{"time":39000,"text":"I should say people who write about science --"},{"time":43000,"text":"and editors would sit down over a couple of beers,"},{"time":45000,"text":"after a hard day of work, and start talking about"},{"time":49000,"text":"some of these incredible perceptions about how the universe works."}]},{"cues":[{"time":54000,"text":"And they would inevitably end up in what I thought was a very bizarre place,"},{"time":59000,"text":"which is ways the world could end very suddenly."},{"time":63000,"text":"And that's what I want to talk about today. (Laughter)"},{"time":68000,"text":"Ah, you laugh, you fools. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":75000,"text":"(Voice: Can we finish up a little early?)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":77000,"text":"(Laughter) Yeah, we need the time!"},{"time":82000,"text":"Stephen Petranek: At first, it all seemed a little fantastical to me, but after challenging a lot of these ideas,"},{"time":88000,"text":"I began to take a lot of them seriously. And then September 11 happened,"},{"time":92000,"text":"and I thought, ah, God,"},{"time":94000,"text":"I can't go to the TED conference and talk about how the world is going to end."},{"time":97000,"text":"Nobody wants to hear that. Not after this!"},{"time":102000,"text":"And that got me into a discussion with some other people, other scientists,"},{"time":106000,"text":"about maybe some other subjects, and one of the guys I talked to,"},{"time":110000,"text":"who was a neuroscientist, said,"},{"time":112000,"text":"\"You know, I think there are a lot of solutions to the problems you brought up,\""},{"time":116000,"text":"and reminds me of Michael's talk yesterday"},{"time":120000,"text":"and his mother saying you can't have a solution if you don't have a problem."},{"time":124000,"text":"So, we went out looking for solutions to ways that the world might end tomorrow,"},{"time":129000,"text":"and lo and behold, we found them."},{"time":132000,"text":"Which leads me to a videotape of a President Bush"},{"time":138000,"text":"press conference from a couple of weeks ago."},{"time":140000,"text":"Can we run that, Andrew?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":142000,"text":"President George W. Bush: Whatever it costs to defend our security,"},{"time":146000,"text":"and whatever it costs to defend our freedom, we must pay it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":151000,"text":"SP: I agree with the president."},{"time":152000,"text":"He wants two trillion dollars to protect us from terrorists next year,"},{"time":158000,"text":"a two-trillion-dollar federal budget, which will land us back into deficit spending real fast."},{"time":164000,"text":"But terrorists aren't the only threat we face."},{"time":167000,"text":"There are really serious calamities staring us in the eye"},{"time":172000,"text":"that we're in the same kind of denial about"},{"time":174000,"text":"that we were about terrorism, and what could've happened on September 11."}]},{"cues":[{"time":180000,"text":"I would propose, therefore, that if we took 10 billion dollars"},{"time":186000,"text":"from that 2.13 trillion dollar budget --"},{"time":189000,"text":"which is two one hundredths of that budget --"},{"time":195000,"text":"and we doled out a billion dollars to each one of these problems"},{"time":199000,"text":"I'm going to talk to you about, the vast majority could be solved,"},{"time":203000,"text":"and the rest we could deal with. So, I hope you find this both fascinating --"},{"time":209000,"text":"I'm fascinated by this kind of stuff, I gotta admit --"},{"time":212000,"text":"to me these are Richard's cockroaches."}]},{"cues":[{"time":218000,"text":"But I also hope, because I think the people in this room can literally change the world,"},{"time":224000,"text":"I hope you take some of this stuff away with you,"},{"time":228000,"text":"and when you have an opportunity to be influential,"},{"time":232000,"text":"that you try to get some heavy-duty money spent on some of these ideas."}]},{"cues":[{"time":236000,"text":"So let's start. Number 10: we lose the will to survive."},{"time":245000,"text":"We live in an incredible age of modern medicine."},{"time":248000,"text":"We are all much healthier than we were 20 years ago."},{"time":252000,"text":"People around the world are getting better medicine --"},{"time":257000,"text":"but mentally, we're falling apart."},{"time":260000,"text":"The World Health Organization now estimates"},{"time":262000,"text":"that one out of five people on the planet is clinically depressed."},{"time":268000,"text":"And the World Health Organization also says that depression is the"},{"time":273000,"text":"biggest epidemic that humankind has ever faced."}]},{"cues":[{"time":279000,"text":"Soon, genetic breakthroughs and even better medicine"},{"time":282000,"text":"are going to allow us to think of 100 as a normal lifespan."},{"time":288000,"text":"A female child born tomorrow, on average -- median -- will live to age 83."},{"time":296000,"text":"Our life longevity is going up almost a year for every year that passes."},{"time":301000,"text":"Now the problem with all of this, getting older,"},{"time":303000,"text":"is that people over 65 are the most likely people to commit suicide."}]},{"cues":[{"time":308000,"text":"So, what are the solutions?"},{"time":310000,"text":"We don't really have mental health insurance in this country,"},{"time":313000,"text":"and it's -- (Applause) -- it's really a crime."},{"time":317000,"text":"Something like 98 percent of all people with depression,"},{"time":321000,"text":"and I mean really severe depression"},{"time":322000,"text":"-- I have a friend with stunningly severe depression"},{"time":327000,"text":"-- this is a curable disease, with present medicine and present technology."},{"time":331000,"text":"But it is often a combination of talk therapy and pills."},{"time":335000,"text":"Pills alone don't do it, especially in clinically depressed people."},{"time":340000,"text":"You ought to be able to go to a psychiatrist or a psychologist,"},{"time":344000,"text":"and put down your 10-dollar copay, and get treated,"},{"time":346000,"text":"just like you do when you got a cut on your arm. It's ridiculous."}]},{"cues":[{"time":350000,"text":"Secondly, drug companies are not going to develop really sophisticated"},{"time":355000,"text":"psychoactive drugs. We know that most mental illnesses have a biological"},{"time":362000,"text":"component that can be dealt with."},{"time":365000,"text":"And we know just an amazing amount more about the brain now than we"},{"time":368000,"text":"did 10 years ago. We need a pump-push from the federal government,"},{"time":373000,"text":"through NIH and National Science -- NSF --"},{"time":378000,"text":"and places like that to start helping the drug companies"},{"time":380000,"text":"develop some advanced psychoactive drugs."}]},{"cues":[{"time":384000,"text":"Moving on. Number nine -- don't laugh -- aliens invade Earth."},{"time":389000,"text":"Ten years ago, you couldn't have found an astronomer --"},{"time":392000,"text":"well, very few astronomers -- in the world who would've told you that"},{"time":395000,"text":"there are any planets anywhere outside our solar system."},{"time":399000,"text":"1995, we found three. The count now is up to 80 --"},{"time":403000,"text":"we're finding about two or three a month."},{"time":407000,"text":"All of the ones we've found, by the way, are in this little, teeny, tiny corner where we live,"},{"time":410000,"text":"in the Milky Way. There must be millions of planets in the Milky Way,"},{"time":416000,"text":"and as Carl Sagan insisted for many years,"},{"time":419000,"text":"and was laughed at for it, there must be billions and billions in the universe."},{"time":424000,"text":"In a few years, NASA is going to launch four or five telescopes out to Jupiter,"},{"time":428000,"text":"where there's less dust, and start looking for Earth-like planets,"},{"time":432000,"text":"which we cannot see with present technology, nor detect."},{"time":436000,"text":"It's becoming obvious that the chance that life does not exist elsewhere in the universe,"},{"time":444000,"text":"and probably fairly close to us, is a fairly remote idea."},{"time":448000,"text":"And the chance that some of it isn't more intelligent than ours is also a remote idea."}]},{"cues":[{"time":454000,"text":"Remember, we've only been an advanced civilization --"},{"time":456000,"text":"an industrial civilization, if you would -- for 200 years."},{"time":460000,"text":"Although every time I go to Pompeii, I'm amazed that they had"},{"time":463000,"text":"the equivalent of a McDonald's on every street corner, too."},{"time":465000,"text":"So, I don't know how much civilization really has progressed since AD 79,"},{"time":469000,"text":"but there's a great likelihood. I really believe this,"},{"time":473000,"text":"and I don't believe in aliens, and I don't believe there are any aliens on the Earth"},{"time":478000,"text":"or anything like that. But there's a likelihood that we will confront a"},{"time":481000,"text":"civilization that is more intelligent than our own."}]},{"cues":[{"time":484000,"text":"Now, what will happen? What if they come to, you know,"},{"time":488000,"text":"suck up our oceans for the hydrogen?"},{"time":491000,"text":"And swat us away like flies, the way we swat away flies when we go into"},{"time":494000,"text":"the rainforest and start logging it."},{"time":497000,"text":"We can look at our own history. The late physicist Gerard O'Neill said,"},{"time":502000,"text":"\"Advanced Western civilization has had a destructive effect"},{"time":505000,"text":"on all primitive civilizations it has come in contact with,"},{"time":509000,"text":"even in those cases where every attempt was made"},{"time":512000,"text":"to protect and guard the primitive civilization.\""},{"time":517000,"text":"If the aliens come visiting, we're the primitive civilization."}]},{"cues":[{"time":521000,"text":"So, what are the solutions to this? (Laughter)"},{"time":530000,"text":"Thank God you can all read!"},{"time":533000,"text":"It may seem ridiculous, but we have a really lousy history of anticipating things like this"},{"time":540000,"text":"and actually being prepared for them."},{"time":542000,"text":"How much energy and money does it take to actually have a plan"},{"time":545000,"text":"to negotiate with an advanced species?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":550000,"text":"Secondly -- and you're going to hear more from me about this --"},{"time":554000,"text":"we have to become an outward-looking, space-faring nation."},{"time":557000,"text":"We have got to develop the"},{"time":558000,"text":"idea that the Earth doesn't last forever,"},{"time":561000,"text":"our sun doesn't last forever."},{"time":563000,"text":"If we want humanity to last forever, we have to colonize the Milky Way."},{"time":568000,"text":"And that is not something that is beyond comprehension at this point."},{"time":574000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":577000,"text":"It'll also help us a lot, if we meet an advanced civilization along the way,"},{"time":581000,"text":"if we're trying to be an advanced civilization. Number eight --"}]},{"cues":[{"time":584000,"text":"(Voice: Steve, that's what I'm doing after TED.) (Laughter) (Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":590000,"text":"SP: You've got it! You've got the job."}]},{"cues":[{"time":593000,"text":"Number eight: the ecosystem collapses."},{"time":595000,"text":"Last July, in Science, the journal Science,"},{"time":600000,"text":"19 oceanographers published a very, very unusual article."},{"time":603000,"text":"It wasn't really a research report; it was a screed."},{"time":606000,"text":"They said, we've been looking at the oceans for a long time now,"},{"time":609000,"text":"and we want to tell you they're not in trouble, they're near collapse."},{"time":613000,"text":"Many other ecosystems on Earth are in real, real danger."},{"time":619000,"text":"We're living in a time of mass extinctions that exceeds the fossil record"},{"time":622000,"text":"by a factor of 10,000."},{"time":625000,"text":"We have lost 25 percent of the unique species in Hawaii in the last 20 years."},{"time":630000,"text":"California is expected to lose 25 percent of its species in the next 40 years."},{"time":636000,"text":"Somewhere in the Amazon forest is the marginal tree."},{"time":640000,"text":"You cut down that tree, the rain forest collapses as an ecosystem."},{"time":644000,"text":"There's really a tree like that out there. That's really what it comes to."},{"time":647000,"text":"And when that ecosystem collapses, it could take a major ecosystem with it,"},{"time":652000,"text":"like our atmosphere. So, what do we do about this? What are the solutions?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":659000,"text":"There is some modeling of ecosystems going on now."},{"time":662000,"text":"The problem with ecosystems is that we understand them so poorly,"},{"time":667000,"text":"that we don't know they're really in trouble until it's almost too late."},{"time":671000,"text":"We need to know earlier that they're getting in trouble,"},{"time":675000,"text":"and we need to be able to pump possible solutions into models."},{"time":679000,"text":"And with the kind of computing power we have now,"},{"time":682000,"text":"there is, as I say, some of this going on, but it needs money."},{"time":685000,"text":"National Science Foundation needs to say -- you know,"},{"time":688000,"text":"almost all the money that's spent on science in this country"},{"time":691000,"text":"comes from the federal government, one way or another."},{"time":694000,"text":"And they get to prioritize, you know?"},{"time":696000,"text":"There are people at the National Science Foundation"},{"time":697000,"text":"who get to say, this is the most important thing."},{"time":700000,"text":"This is one of the things they ought to be thinking more about."}]},{"cues":[{"time":702000,"text":"Secondly, we need to create huge biodiversity reserves on the planet,"},{"time":705000,"text":"and start moving them around."},{"time":707000,"text":"There's been an experiment for the last four or five years on the Georges Bank,"},{"time":711000,"text":"or the Grand Banks off of Newfoundland. It's a no-take fishing zone."},{"time":715000,"text":"They can't fish there for a radius of 200 miles."},{"time":718000,"text":"And an amazing thing has happened: almost all the fish have come back,"},{"time":721000,"text":"and they're reproducing like crazy. We're going to have to start doing this"},{"time":725000,"text":"around the globe. We're going to have to have no-take zones."},{"time":727000,"text":"We're going to have to say, no more logging in the Amazon for 20 years."},{"time":731000,"text":"Let it recover, before we start logging again."},{"time":733000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":739000,"text":"Number seven: particle accelerator mishap."},{"time":743000,"text":"You all remember Ted Kaczynski, the Unabomber?"},{"time":746000,"text":"One of the things he raved about was that a particle accelerator experiment"},{"time":750000,"text":"could go haywire and set off a chain reaction that would destroy the world."},{"time":755000,"text":"A lot of very sober-minded physicists, believe it or not,"},{"time":757000,"text":"have had exactly the same thought."},{"time":760000,"text":"This spring -- there's a collider at Brookhaven, on Long Island --"},{"time":763000,"text":"this spring, it's going to have an experiment in which it creates black holes."},{"time":767000,"text":"They are expecting to create little, tiny black holes."},{"time":771000,"text":"They expect them to evaporate. (Laughter)"},{"time":778000,"text":"I hope they're right. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":781000,"text":"Other collider experiments -- there's one that's going to take place next summer"},{"time":785000,"text":"at CERN -- have the possibility of creating something called strangelets,"},{"time":789000,"text":"which are kind of like antimatter. Whenever they hit other matter, they destroy it"},{"time":793000,"text":"and obliterate it. Most physicists say that the accelerators we have now"},{"time":797000,"text":"are not really powerful enough to create black holes and strangelets"},{"time":800000,"text":"that we need to worry about, and they're probably right."},{"time":803000,"text":"But, all around the world, in Japan, in Canada,"},{"time":807000,"text":"there's talk about this, of reviving this in the United States."},{"time":809000,"text":"We shut one down that was going to be big."},{"time":811000,"text":"But there's talk of building very big accelerators."},{"time":815000,"text":"What can we do about this? What are the solutions?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":818000,"text":"We've got the fox watching the henhouse here."},{"time":820000,"text":"We need to -- we need the advice of particle physicists to talk about particle physics"},{"time":826000,"text":"and what should be done in particle physics,"},{"time":828000,"text":"but we need some outside thinking and watchdogging"},{"time":833000,"text":"of what's going on with these experiments."}]},{"cues":[{"time":836000,"text":"Secondly, we have a natural laboratory surrounding the Earth."},{"time":839000,"text":"We have an electromagnetic field around the Earth,"},{"time":841000,"text":"and it's constantly bombarded by high-energy particles, like protons."},{"time":846000,"text":"And in my opinion, we don't spend enough time"},{"time":850000,"text":"looking at that natural laboratory and figuring out first what's safe to do on Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":857000,"text":"Number six: biotech disaster."},{"time":860000,"text":"It's one of my favorite ones, because we've done several stories on Bt corn."},{"time":863000,"text":"Bt corn is a corn that creates its own pesticide to kill a corn borer."},{"time":869000,"text":"You may of heard of it -- heard it called StarLink,"},{"time":873000,"text":"especially when all those taco shells were taken out of the supermarkets"},{"time":877000,"text":"about a year and a half ago."},{"time":879000,"text":"This stuff was supposed to only be feed for animals in the United States,"},{"time":883000,"text":"and it got into the human food supply, and somebody should've figured out"},{"time":887000,"text":"that it would get in the human food supply very easily."},{"time":890000,"text":"But the thing that's alarming is a couple of months ago, in Mexico,"},{"time":893000,"text":"where Bt corn and all genetically altered corn is totally illegal,"},{"time":897000,"text":"they found Bt corn genes in wild corn plants."},{"time":901000,"text":"Now, corn originated, we think, in Mexico."},{"time":904000,"text":"This is the genetic biodiversity storehouse of corn."},{"time":909000,"text":"This brings back a skepticism that has gone away recently,"},{"time":915000,"text":"that superweeds and superpests could spread around the world,"},{"time":919000,"text":"from biotechnology, that literally could destroy the world's food supply"},{"time":924000,"text":"in very short order."}]},{"cues":[{"time":926000,"text":"So, what do we do about that?"},{"time":930000,"text":"We treat biotechnology with the same scrutiny we apply to nuclear power plants."},{"time":935000,"text":"It's that simple. This is an amazingly unregulated field."},{"time":938000,"text":"When the StarLink disaster happened, there was a battle between the"},{"time":941000,"text":"EPA and the FDA over who really had authority, and over what parts of this,"},{"time":946000,"text":"and they didn't get it straightened out for months. That's kind of crazy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":950000,"text":"Number five, one of my favorites: reversal of the Earth's magnetic field."},{"time":955000,"text":"Believe it or not, this happens every few hundred thousand years,"},{"time":958000,"text":"and has happened many times in our history."},{"time":960000,"text":"North Pole goes to the South, South Pole goes to the North, and vice versa."},{"time":965000,"text":"But what happens, as this occurs,"},{"time":968000,"text":"is that we lose our magnetic field around the Earth over the period of about 100 years,"},{"time":974000,"text":"and that means that all these cosmic rays and particles"},{"time":976000,"text":"that are to come streaming at us from the sun,"},{"time":979000,"text":"that this field protects us from, are -- well, basically, we're gonna fry. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":992000,"text":"(Voice: Steve, I have some additional hats downstairs.)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":996000,"text":"SP: So, what can we do about this? Oh, by the way, we're overdue."},{"time":1000000,"text":"It's been 780,000 years since this happened."},{"time":1002000,"text":"So, it should have happened about 480,000 years ago."},{"time":1005000,"text":"Oh, and here's one other thing."},{"time":1007000,"text":"Scientists think now our magnetic field may be diminished by about five percent."},{"time":1015000,"text":"So, maybe we're in the throes of it."},{"time":1019000,"text":"One of the problems of trying to figure out how healthy the Earth is,"},{"time":1023000,"text":"is that we have -- you know, we don't have good weather data from 60 years ago,"},{"time":1027000,"text":"much less data on things like the ozone layer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1031000,"text":"So, there's a fairly simple solution to this."},{"time":1035000,"text":"There's going to be a lot of cheap rocketry that's going to come online"},{"time":1038000,"text":"in about six or seven years"},{"time":1040000,"text":"that gets us into the low atmosphere very cheaply."},{"time":1044000,"text":"You know, we can make ozone from car tailpipes."},{"time":1047000,"text":"It's not hard: it's just three oxygen atoms."},{"time":1050000,"text":"If you brought the entire ozone layer down to the surface of the Earth,"},{"time":1054000,"text":"it would be the thickness of two pennies, at 14 pounds per square inch."},{"time":1057000,"text":"You don't need that much up there."},{"time":1060000,"text":"We need to learn how to repair and replenish the Earth's ozone layer."},{"time":1063000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1067000,"text":"Number four: giant solar flares."},{"time":1070000,"text":"Solar flares are enormous magnetic outbursts from the Sun"},{"time":1074000,"text":"that bombard the Earth with high-speed subatomic particles."},{"time":1078000,"text":"So far, our atmosphere has done, and our magnetic field has done"},{"time":1081000,"text":"pretty well protecting us from this."},{"time":1084000,"text":"Occasionally, we get a flare from the Sun that causes havoc"},{"time":1088000,"text":"with communications and so forth, and electricity."},{"time":1092000,"text":"But the alarming thing is that astronomers recently have been studying"},{"time":1095000,"text":"stars that are similar to our Sun,"},{"time":1097000,"text":"and they've found that a number of them, when they're about the age of our Sun,"},{"time":1101000,"text":"brighten by a factor of as much as 20. Doesn't last for very long."},{"time":1106000,"text":"And they think these are super-flares, millions of times more powerful"},{"time":1108000,"text":"than any flares we've had from our Sun so far."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1113000,"text":"Obviously, we don't want one of those. (Laughter)"},{"time":1117000,"text":"There's a flip side to it. In studying stars"},{"time":1119000,"text":"like our Sun, we've found that they go through periods of diminishment,"},{"time":1123000,"text":"when their total amount of energy that's expelled from them"},{"time":1127000,"text":"goes down by maybe one percent."},{"time":1129000,"text":"One percent doesn't sound like a lot, but it would cause one hell of an ice age here."},{"time":1133000,"text":"So, what can we do about this?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1135000,"text":"(Laughter) Start terraforming Mars. This is one of my favorite subjects."},{"time":1138000,"text":"I wrote a story about this in Life magazine in 1993."},{"time":1142000,"text":"This is rocket science, but it's not hard rocket science."},{"time":1146000,"text":"Everything that we need to make an atmosphere on Mars,"},{"time":1149000,"text":"and to make a livable planet on Mars, is probably there."},{"time":1153000,"text":"And you just, literally, have to send little nuclear factories up there"},{"time":1159000,"text":"that gobble up the iron oxide on the surface of Mars and spit out the oxygen."},{"time":1164000,"text":"The problem is it takes 300 years to terraform Mars, minimum."},{"time":1168000,"text":"Really more like 500 years to do it right."},{"time":1171000,"text":"There's no reason why we shouldn't start now. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1175000,"text":"Number three -- isn't this stuff cool? (Laughter)"},{"time":1182000,"text":"A new global epidemic. People have been at war with germs"},{"time":1185000,"text":"ever since there have been people,"},{"time":1186000,"text":"and from time to time, the germs sure get the upper hand."},{"time":1190000,"text":"In 1918, we had a flu epidemic in the United States that killed 20 million people."},{"time":1195000,"text":"That was back when the population was around 100 million people."},{"time":1199000,"text":"The bubonic plague in Europe, in the Middle Ages,"},{"time":1202000,"text":"killed one out of four Europeans."},{"time":1206000,"text":"AIDS is coming back. Ebola seems to be rearing its head"},{"time":1210000,"text":"with much too much frequency,"},{"time":1213000,"text":"and old diseases like cholera are becoming resistant to antibiotics."},{"time":1218000,"text":"We've all learned what -- the kind of panic that can occur"},{"time":1220000,"text":"when an old disease rears its head, like anthrax."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1225000,"text":"The worst possibility is that a very simple germ, like staph,"},{"time":1232000,"text":"for which we have one antibiotic that still works, mutates."},{"time":1237000,"text":"And we know staph can do amazing things."},{"time":1239000,"text":"A staph cell can be next to a muscle cell in your body and borrow genes from it"},{"time":1244000,"text":"when antibiotics come, and change and mutate."},{"time":1248000,"text":"The danger is that some germ like staph will be --"},{"time":1250000,"text":"will mutate into something that's really virulent, very contagious,"},{"time":1255000,"text":"and will sweep through populations before we can do anything about it."},{"time":1259000,"text":"That's happened before. About 12,000 years ago,"},{"time":1261000,"text":"there was a massive wave of mammal extinctions in the Americas,"},{"time":1266000,"text":"and that is thought to have been a virulent disease."},{"time":1269000,"text":"So, what can we do about it?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1270000,"text":"It is nuts. We give antibiotics -- (Applause) --"},{"time":1276000,"text":"every cow, every lamb, every chicken, they get antibiotics every day, all."},{"time":1281000,"text":"You know, you go to a restaurant, you eat fish, I got news for you,"},{"time":1283000,"text":"it's all farmed. You know, you gotta ask when you go to a restaurant if it's a wild fish,"},{"time":1287000,"text":"cause they're not going to tell you. We're giving away the code."},{"time":1290000,"text":"This is like being at war and giving somebody your secret code."},{"time":1293000,"text":"We're telling the germs out there how to fight us."},{"time":1298000,"text":"We gotta fix that. We gotta outlaw that right away."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1300000,"text":"Secondly, our public health system, as we saw with anthrax, is a real disaster."},{"time":1304000,"text":"We have a real, major outbreak of disease in the United States,"},{"time":1310000,"text":"we are not prepared to cope with it."},{"time":1312000,"text":"Now, there is money in the federal budget, next year,"},{"time":1314000,"text":"to build up the public health service."},{"time":1316000,"text":"But I don't think to any extent that it really needs to be done."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1321000,"text":"Number two -- my favorite -- we meet a rogue black hole."},{"time":1325000,"text":"You know, 10 years ago, or 15 years ago, really,"},{"time":1328000,"text":"you walk into an astronomy convention, and you say,"},{"time":1330000,"text":"\"You know, there's probably a black hole at the center of every galaxy,\""},{"time":1333000,"text":"and they're going to hoot you off the stage."},{"time":1335000,"text":"And now, if you went into one of those conventions and you said,"},{"time":1337000,"text":"\"Well, I don't think black holes are out there,\" they'd hoot you off the stage."},{"time":1341000,"text":"Our comprehension of the way the universe works is really --"},{"time":1344000,"text":"has just gained unbelievably in recent years."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1349000,"text":"We think that there are about 10 million dead stars in the Milky Way alone, our galaxy."},{"time":1356000,"text":"And these stars have compressed down to maybe something like 12, 15 miles wide,"},{"time":1360000,"text":"and they are black holes. And they are gobbling up everything around them,"},{"time":1363000,"text":"including light, which is why we can't see them."},{"time":1368000,"text":"Most of them should be in orbit around something."},{"time":1371000,"text":"But galaxies are very violent places, and things can be spun out of orbit."},{"time":1375000,"text":"And also, space is incredibly vast."},{"time":1378000,"text":"So even if you flung a million of these things out of orbit,"},{"time":1383000,"text":"the chances that one would actually hit us is fairly remote."},{"time":1386000,"text":"But it only has to get close, about a billion miles away, one of these things."},{"time":1394000,"text":"About a billion miles away, here's what happens to Earth's orbit:"},{"time":1397000,"text":"it becomes elliptical instead of circular."},{"time":1400000,"text":"And for three months out of the year,"},{"time":1402000,"text":"the surface temperatures go up to 150 to 180."},{"time":1406000,"text":"For three months out of the year, they go to 50 below zero."},{"time":1409000,"text":"That won't work too well. What can we do about this?"},{"time":1411000,"text":"And this is my scariest. (Laughter)"},{"time":1419000,"text":"I don't have a good answer for this one."},{"time":1424000,"text":"Again, we gotta think about being a colonizing race."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1428000,"text":"And finally, number one: biggest danger to life as we know it, I think,"},{"time":1433000,"text":"a really big asteroid heads for Earth."},{"time":1436000,"text":"The important thing to remember here -- this is not a question of if,"},{"time":1440000,"text":"this is a question of when, and how big."},{"time":1444000,"text":"In 1908, just a 200-foot piece of a comet"},{"time":1448000,"text":"exploded over Siberia and flattened forests for maybe 100 miles."},{"time":1452000,"text":"It had the effect of about 1,000 Hiroshima bombs."},{"time":1457000,"text":"Astronomers estimate that little asteroids like that come about every hundred years."},{"time":1462000,"text":"In 1989, a large asteroid passed 400,000 miles away from Earth."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1469000,"text":"Nothing to worry about, right?"},{"time":1471000,"text":"It passed directly through Earth's orbit. We were in that that spot six hours earlier."},{"time":1481000,"text":"A small asteroid, say a half mile wide, would touch off firestorms"},{"time":1485000,"text":"followed by severe global cooling from the debris kicked up --"},{"time":1489000,"text":"Carl Sagan's nuclear winter thing."},{"time":1491000,"text":"An asteroid five miles wide causes major extinctions."},{"time":1495000,"text":"We think the one that got the dinosaurs was about five miles wide."},{"time":1498000,"text":"Where are they? There's something called the Kuiper belt,"},{"time":1501000,"text":"which -- some people think Pluto's not a planet,"},{"time":1506000,"text":"that's where Pluto is, it's in the Kuiper belt."},{"time":1509000,"text":"There's also something a little farther out, called the Oort cloud."},{"time":1511000,"text":"There are about 100,000 balls of ice and rock -- comets, really --"},{"time":1517000,"text":"out there, that are 50 miles in diameter or more,"},{"time":1521000,"text":"and they regularly take a little spin,"},{"time":1523000,"text":"in towards the Sun and pass reasonably close to us."},{"time":1529000,"text":"Of more concern, I think, is the asteroids that exist between Mars and Jupiter."},{"time":1538000,"text":"The folks at the Sloan Digital Sky Survey told us last fall --"},{"time":1541000,"text":"they're making the first map of the universe, three-dimensional map of the universe --"},{"time":1545000,"text":"that there are probably 700,000 asteroids between Mars and Jupiter"},{"time":1550000,"text":"that are a half a mile big or bigger."},{"time":1555000,"text":"So you say, yeah, well, what are really the chances of this happening?"},{"time":1561000,"text":"Andrew, can you put that chart up?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1564000,"text":"This is a chart that Dr. Clark Chapman at the Southwest Research Institute"},{"time":1569000,"text":"presented to Congress a few years ago."},{"time":1572000,"text":"You'll notice that the chance of an asteroid-slash-comet impact killing you"},{"time":1576000,"text":"is about one in 20,000, according to the work they've done."},{"time":1579000,"text":"Now look at the one right below that."},{"time":1581000,"text":"Passenger aircraft crash, one in 20,000."},{"time":1586000,"text":"We spend an awful lot of money trying to be sure that we don't die in airplane accidents,"},{"time":1591000,"text":"and we're not spending hardly anything on this. And yet, this is completely preventable."},{"time":1598000,"text":"We finally have, just in the last year, the technology to stop this cold."},{"time":1602000,"text":"Could we have the solutions?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1604000,"text":"NASA's spending three million dollars a year, three million bucks --"},{"time":1608000,"text":"that is like pocket change -- to search for asteroids."},{"time":1611000,"text":"Because we can actually figure out every asteroid that's out there,"},{"time":1616000,"text":"and if it might hit Earth, and when it might hit Earth."},{"time":1619000,"text":"And they're trying to do that."},{"time":1620000,"text":"But it's going to take them 10 years, at spending three million dollars a year,"},{"time":1624000,"text":"and even then, they claim they'll only have about 80 percent of them catalogued."},{"time":1628000,"text":"Comets are a tougher act."},{"time":1630000,"text":"We don't really have the technology to predict comet trajectories,"},{"time":1633000,"text":"or when one with our name on it might arrive."},{"time":1636000,"text":"But we would have lots of time, if we see it coming."},{"time":1639000,"text":"We really need a dedicated observatory."},{"time":1642000,"text":"You'll notice that a lot of comets are named after people you never heard of,"},{"time":1645000,"text":"amateur astronomers? That's because nobody's looking for them, except amateurs."},{"time":1649000,"text":"We need a dedicated observatory that looks for comets."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1653000,"text":"Part two of the solutions: we need to figure out how to blow up an asteroid,"},{"time":1658000,"text":"or alter its trajectory. Now, a year ago, we did an amazing thing."},{"time":1662000,"text":"We sent a probe out to this asteroid belt,"},{"time":1664000,"text":"called NEAR, Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous."},{"time":1667000,"text":"And these guys orbited a 30 -- or no, about a 22-mile long asteroid called Eros."},{"time":1675000,"text":"And then, of course, you know, they pulled one of those sneaky NASA things,"},{"time":1678000,"text":"where they had extra batteries and extra gas aboard and everything,"},{"time":1681000,"text":"and then, at the last minute, they landed."},{"time":1683000,"text":"When the mission was over, they actually landed on the thing."},{"time":1686000,"text":"We have landed a rocket ship on an asteroid. It's not a big deal."},{"time":1691000,"text":"Now, the trouble with just sending a bomb out for this thing"},{"time":1694000,"text":"is that you don't have anything to push against in space, because there's no air."},{"time":1698000,"text":"A nuclear explosion is just as hot,"},{"time":1700000,"text":"but we don't really have anything big enough to melt a 22-mile long asteroid,"},{"time":1706000,"text":"or vaporize it, would be more like it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1708000,"text":"But we can learn to land on these asteroids that have our name on them"},{"time":1713000,"text":"and put something like a small ion propulsion motor on it,"},{"time":1717000,"text":"which would gently, slowly, after a period of time, push it into a different trajectory,"},{"time":1722000,"text":"which, if we've done our math right, would keep it from hitting Earth."},{"time":1725000,"text":"This is just a matter of finding 'em, going there, and doing something about it."},{"time":1730000,"text":"I know your head is spinning from all this stuff."},{"time":1733000,"text":"Yikes! So many big threats!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1736000,"text":"The thing, I think, to remember, is September 11."},{"time":1738000,"text":"We don't want to get caught flat-footed again."},{"time":1741000,"text":"We know about this stuff."},{"time":1743000,"text":"Science has the power to predict the future in many cases now."},{"time":1747000,"text":"Knowledge is power."},{"time":1749000,"text":"The worst thing we can do is say, jeez, I got enough to worry about"},{"time":1754000,"text":"without worrying about an asteroid. (Laughter)"},{"time":1760000,"text":"That's a mistake that could literally cost us our future."},{"time":1763000,"text":"Thank you."}]}]}